In the grammar above the only non-terminal that can produce the terminal symbol t3 is NT20:

 NT20 → 't3'

No other production yields t3.

For two consecutive t3’s to appear in a derived string the parse tree must contain a rule whose two immediate children both ultimately yield t3, i.e. a binary production whose left part ends with a t3 and whose right part starts with a t3.

The only rules in which NT20 occurs on the right-hand side are

 NT12 → NT20 NT26  (first symbol t3 …)  
 NT48 → NT49 NT20  (… last symbol t3)

• In NT12 → NT20 NT26, the first t3 comes from NT20, but NT26 can never start with t3 (its first symbol is produced by NT33 or NT4, and neither of those can yield t3 because only NT20 makes t3).  
• In NT48 → NT49 NT20, the second t3 comes from NT20, yet NT49 can never end with t3 for the same reason—NT49’s expansions never contain NT20 at the far right.

Hence no rule combination can place two NT20’s (and therefore two t3’s) next to each other. The grammar can generate at most single, separated t3 tokens.

The string to be checked contains “… t3 t3 …” (positions 10 and 11), two consecutive t3’s. Since such a pattern is impossible for this grammar, the string cannot be generated.

No

The start symbol ​S​ can expand in only two ways:

1. S → NT45 NT9  
2. S → NT22 NT18  

The given string begins with the terminal t5.

────────────────────────
1. The alternative S → NT22 NT18
────────────────────────
NT22 has just two productions:

• NT22 → 't0'            (first symbol t0)  
• NT22 → NT23 NT15, and NT23 → 't8' (first symbol t8)

Hence every string derived from NT22 must start with either t0 or t8, never with t5.  
Therefore the derivation S → NT22 NT18 cannot produce the required string.

────────────────────────
2. The alternative S → NT45 NT9
────────────────────────
NT45 can expand only as

a) NT45 → NT44 NT7  
b) NT45 → NT11 NT6  
c) NT45 → NT23 NT15  

c) starts with t8 (NT23 → 't8') – ruled out.

b) ends with t8 (because NT6 → 't8'), so any string derived from (b) ends with t8, but the 30-th token in the target prefix (the portion that NT45 would have to generate) is t6, not t8 – ruled out.

For a), the first symbol produced by NT45 is the first symbol produced by NT44 (since NT7 comes after it).  
NT44 may be

• NT44 → 't9'   (first symbol t9)  
• NT44 → 't8'   (first symbol t8)  
• NT44 → NT32 NT3, whose first symbol is the first symbol of NT32.

NT32, however, can only be

• NT32 → NT7 NT11 (first symbol NT7 → 't1')  
• NT32 → NT47 NT37 (first symbol NT47 → 't8')

So every possible expansion of NT44, and therefore of NT45, begins with t9, t8, or t1 – never with t5.

Consequently, NT45 cannot derive a string whose first symbol is t5.

────────────────────────
Conclusion
────────────────────────
Neither S → NT22 NT18 nor S → NT45 NT9 can start with the required initial terminal t5. Hence the grammar cannot generate the given string.

No

In the grammar the only way to obtain the terminal symbol t4 is by using the production  

 NT10 → 't4'  

(no other non-terminal has a terminal production for t4, and the grammar contains no ε-productions or unit productions of the form A → B).  
Hence every occurrence of t4 in any generated string must correspond to a leaf labelled NT10.

For two successive t4’s to appear in a derived string there must be some production whose right–hand side contains two symbols each capable of deriving a single t4, i.e. a rule of the form X → NT10 NT10 (or equivalent with two symbols that both eventually reduce to NT10).  

Examining the grammar, NT10 appears on the right–hand side only in the following rules:

 NT10 → NT22 NT40  
 NT10 → NT38 NT38  
 NT10 → NT25 NT15  
 NT10 → NT48 NT48  
 NT10 → NT5 NT6  
 NT46 → NT18 NT10  
 NT50 → NT4 NT10  

In every case it occurs at most once, never twice. Therefore the grammar can never place two NT10’s (and thus two t4’s) next to each other in any derived string.

The given string contains the consecutive terminals “… t4 t4 …” (positions 33 and 34).  
Since the grammar cannot generate two adjacent t4’s, the entire string cannot be produced by the grammar.

No

To get the first symbol of the derived string we only have to look at the first non-terminal that S can expand to.

S has exactly two possibilities  
  S → NT45 NT9 or S → NT22 NT18

So the first terminal of any sentence in the language must come from NT45 (first rule) or from NT22 (second rule).

1. First terminals obtainable from NT45  
   NT45 → NT44 NT7  (first symbol comes from NT44)  
   NT45 → NT11 NT6  (first symbol comes from NT11)  
   NT45 → NT23 NT15  (first symbol is the terminal produced by NT23)

   – NT44 can produce only t8 or t9.  
   – NT23 produces only t8.  
   – NT11’s first symbol ultimately comes from NT8, NT34 or another NT45;
     tracing every possibility shows the leading terminals are drawn from  
     {t1, t5, t6, t7, t8, t9}.  
   Hence NT45 can start with t1, t5, t6, t7, t8 or t9 – never with t2.

2. First terminals obtainable from NT22  
   NT22 → 't0'    (first symbol t0)  
   NT22 → NT23 NT15  (first symbol t8, because NT23 → 't8')

   So NT22 can start only with t0 or t8.

Therefore, regardless of which rule for S is chosen, the very first terminal that can be produced is drawn from  
{t0, t1, t5, t6, t7, t8, t9}.  
The grammar can never place t2 at the beginning of any generated string.

The string we must test begins with t2, so it cannot be generated by the grammar.

No
